  <!-- SEO Intro -->
  <div class="fio-card">
    <h3 class="fio-h3">What Is a Covered Call?</h3>
    <p class="fio-p">
      A <strong>covered call</strong> is an options income strategy where you <strong>sell a call option</strong> against
      <strong>100 shares</strong> of stock you already own. In exchange, you collect <strong>premium</strong> (income).
    </p>
    <p class="fio-p">
      In simple terms: you’re getting paid for agreeing to sell your shares at a specific price (the <strong>strike</strong>)
      by a specific date (the <strong>expiration</strong>).
    </p>

    <div class="fio-grid2">
      <div class="fio-mini">
        <h4 class="fio-h4">Best Market Condition <span class="fio-chip">Neutral → Slightly Bullish</span></h4>
        <p class="fio-p fio-note">Covered calls work best when you expect the stock to stay flat or rise slowly.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="fio-mini">
        <h4 class="fio-h4">The Trade-Off <span class="fio-chip">Income vs Upside</span></h4>
        <p class="fio-p fio-note">You generate income, but you cap upside above your strike price.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- How it Works -->
  <div class="fio-card">
    <h3 class="fio-h3">How Covered Calls Work (5-Step Checklist)</h3>

    <div class="fio-grid2">

      <div class="fio-mini">
        <h4 class="fio-h4">Step 1: Own 100 Shares</h4>
        <ul class="fio-list fio-note">
          <li>Pick a stock/ETF you’re comfortable holding.</li>
          <li>Prefer liquid names (tight bid/ask spreads).</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="fio-mini">
        <h4 class="fio-h4">Step 2: Choose a Strike (Delta Guide)</h4>
        <p class="fio-p fio-note">
          A common starting point is around <strong>0.30 delta</strong> — it balances decent premium with a lower chance of assignment.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="fio-mini">
        <h4 class="fio-h4">Step 3: Pick Expiration (DTE)</h4>
        <ul class="fio-list fio-note">
          <li><strong>7–10 DTE:</strong> faster cycles, smaller premium</li>
          <li><strong>21–60 DTE:</strong> bigger premium, fewer adjustments</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="fio-mini">
        <h4 class="fio-h4">Step 4: Sell the Call</h4>
        <p class="fio-p fio-note">
          Premium is credited immediately. That premium can reduce your effective cost basis on the shares.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="fio-mini">
        <h4 class="fio-h4">Step 5: Two Outcomes</h4>
        <div class="fio-tablewrap">
          <table class="fio-table" aria-label="Covered call outcomes table">
            <thead>
              <tr>
                <th>If stock stays below strike</th>
                <th>If stock goes above strike</th>
              </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr>
                <td>Option expires (or becomes cheap to buy back)</td>
                <td>Shares may be assigned (sold at the strike)</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>You keep shares + premium</td>
                <td>You keep premium + realize stock gain up to strike</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>You can sell another call next cycle</td>
                <td>Your upside is capped above the strike</td>
              </tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>
        <p class="fio-p fio-note fio-muted" style="margin-top:10px;">
          Key rule: choose a strike you’d genuinely be okay selling at.
        </p>
      </div>

    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Profit Target -->
  <div class="fio-card">
    <h3 class="fio-h3">Profit Target (Why We Don’t Always Hold to Expiration)</h3>
    <p class="fio-p">
      Many traders hold covered calls until expiration — but a cleaner approach is using a
      <strong>profit target</strong> (often <strong>50–70%</strong> of max premium) to reduce surprise risk and lock gains sooner.
    </p>
    <ul class="fio-list">
      <li><strong>Lock gains earlier</strong> instead of waiting for the last dollars.</li>
      <li><strong>Theta (time decay)</strong> often helps you hit targets without a big move.</li>
      <li><strong>Recycle trades sooner</strong> to stack premium over time.</li>
    </ul>

    <div class="fio-divider"></div>

    <div class="fio-mini">
      <p class="fio-p"><strong>Simple Example</strong></p>
      <p class="fio-p fio-note">
        You sell a call for $1.00 ($100). If it drops to $0.50, you can buy it back and keep ~$50 profit — then sell another call to keep stacking income.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- When to Use -->
  <div class="fio-card">
    <h3 class="fio-h3">When Covered Calls Make Sense</h3>
    <ul class="fio-list">
      <li>You already own shares and want additional income.</li>
      <li>You’re <strong>neutral to slightly bullish</strong> short-term.</li>
      <li>You want to reduce cost basis (premium offsets some downside).</li>
      <li>You’re okay selling shares at your strike price.</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <!-- Example -->
  <div class="fio-card">
    <h3 class="fio-h3">Covered Call Example (Simple Mechanics)</h3>
    <p class="fio-p">
      Here’s the structure (numbers change based on the options chain — focus on the mechanics):
    </p>
    <ul class="fio-list">
      <li><strong>You own:</strong> 100 shares</li>
      <li><strong>You sell:</strong> 1 call at a chosen strike + expiration</li>
      <li><strong>You collect:</strong> premium (income)</li>
    </ul>

    <div class="fio-divider"></div>

    <div class="fio-grid2">
      <div class="fio-mini">
        <h4 class="fio-h4">Outcome A: Stock stays below strike</h4>
        <ul class="fio-list fio-note">
          <li>You keep your shares</li>
          <li>You keep the premium</li>
          <li>You can sell another call next cycle</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="fio-mini">
        <h4 class="fio-h4">Outcome B: Stock goes above strike</h4>
        <ul class="fio-list fio-note">
          <li>Shares may be assigned (sold at strike)</li>
          <li>You still keep the premium</li>
          <li>You’re capped above the strike (by design)</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="fio-divider"></div>

    <p class="fio-p">
      Covered calls are “boring” on purpose — the goal is repeatable income and cleaner decision-making.
    </p>
  </div>

